		<img width="1694" height="814" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="Titan submersible" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate.jpg 1694w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate-1200x577.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-oceangate-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 1694px) 100vw, 1694px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">In June 2023, a costly search revealed that the missing <em>Titan</em> submersible had imploded en route to the wreckage of the <em>Titanic</em>, killing its five passengers. The Marine Institute at Memorial University in Newfoundland and Labrador partnered with OceanGate, the company that owned and operated the submersible. Photo by Imago/Alamy Stock Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">A Canadian University’s Curious Connection to the Titan Submersible Disaster</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">The Marine Institute at Memorial University in Newfoundland and Labrador partnered with OceanGate—but why?</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/laura-trethewey/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Laura Trethewey</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						November 7, 2023 | 1,400 words, about 7 minutes					</aside>
				</header>

